<h1>Modularity and the Craft of Strategy: In conversation with HBS Emerita Professor Carliss Baldwin</h1>
<p>Sir John Soane's Drawing Office, Sir John Soane's Museum, London. Photo: Gareth Gardner, 2023</p>
<p>Every strategist operates with a mental model of how their organization works. Most of those models are incomplete. They capture markets, competitors, capabilities, and financial flows. They often don&rsquo;t capture the thing that determines how all of those elements interact: the architecture of the technology itself.</p>
<p>This omission was always a limitation. Today, as organizations race to integrate LLM technology into their operations, build AI-native businesses, and reconfigure how knowledge work gets done, it risks becoming a serious vulnerability. The technological shock of generative AI is changing how organizations must be structured, not just what they do, including where their boundaries should sit, and which parts of their value chains are becoming more or less modular in entirely new ways. Leaders navigating these decisions without a mental model for understanding how technology shapes organizations are at a disadvantage.</p>
<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carliss_Y._Baldwin">Carliss Y. Baldwin</a> has spent four decades working on this problem. A professor emerita at Harvard Business School, Baldwin has produced one of the most rigorous and far-reaching bodies of work on the relationship between technology, design, and organizational structure. Her two-volume Design Rules &mdash; <a href="https://direct.mit.edu/books/monograph/1856/Design-Rules-Volume-1The-Power-of-Modularity">the first published in 2000</a>, <a href="https://direct.mit.edu/books/oa-monograph/5887/Design-Rules-Volume-2How-Technology-Shapes">the second in 2024</a> &mdash; offers a set of concepts that belong in every strategist's toolkit: modularity, design rules, option value, mirroring, bottlenecks, and the spectrum of complementarity. Together, they constitute a theory of how technology shapes organizations that is as relevant to the age of AI as it was to the age of the personal computer. They&rsquo;ve long been core to how I think, and so I was delighted she agreed to speak with me recently.</p>
<p>This post overviews Baldwin&rsquo;s work for strategy leaders, explains her core frameworks, maps them to McKinsey&rsquo;s Building Blocks of Strategy Design, Mobilization, and Execution, and demonstrates how to see the other curations I have done in recent posts combine into a library of strategy modules.</p>
<p>This is a long post, in part to ensure its usefulness for use with GenAI, and so if you are short on time, I encourage you to explore its insights with your favorite chatbot. I have set up this link to make feeding this article to Claude, Gemini, and ChatGPT easy.</p>
