</ul>
<p>This composability has a practical implication. The abundance of strategic frameworks and techniques available to leaders today that I described recently in my post on the Taming of Scarcity and Problems of Plenty in Strategy (<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/taming-scarcity-problems-plenty-strategy-whitney-d-zimmerman-covse/?trackingId=h7f2rnmFTI%2B6I96k0bQyKg%3D%3D">LinkedIn</a>, <a href="https://medium.com/@whitneyzim/the-taming-of-scarcity-and-problems-of-plenty-in-strategy-af4a70bdaa17">Medium</a>, <a href="https://substack.com/home/post/p-187236655">Substack</a>) is, to use Baldwin's language, a design problem. Without a shared architecture, each new framework is another disconnected input competing for attention &mdash; valuable in isolation, difficult to integrate. With a shared architecture, new thinking has a place to land. A strategy leader who has internalized the building blocks can encounter a new framework, identify which activities it enriches, and integrate it without losing coherence. Generative AI makes this even more powerful: a strategist working with AI that understands both the building blocks and the techniques available within each one can rapidly curate and assemble a fit-for-purpose methodology from the best available thinking. This is, at its core, Baldwin's insight about modularity making abundance productive, applied to the craft of strategy itself.</p>
<p>There is an implication here for those building AI-enabled tools for strategy and decision-making as well. Baldwin's theory predicts that the tools that create the most value in a modular system are those that conform to a shared architecture, producing outputs which can be integrated into a broader system of activity at clearly defined interfaces. An AI agent for competitive assessment, scenario generation, or strategic option evaluation creates far more value if its outputs are designed to plug into a strategy process at a known point, with information structured in a way that connects to what comes before and after it. Tools that operate as standalone black boxes &mdash; no matter how sophisticated internally &mdash; face the same challenge Baldwin identifies in any unmodularized system: they are hard to test, hard to combine, and dependent on manual integration. The most valuable strategy tools of the coming years will likely be those that are designed to be modular components of a larger process, not self-contained solutions.</p>
<p>Baldwin's central insight is that modularity is what makes abundance productive rather than problematic. Modularity turned the overwhelming complexity of computer design &mdash; where the space of possible configurations was astronomical &mdash; into the most innovative, interdisciplinary, productivity-driving industry in history. It did this not by reducing complexity but by structuring it. McKinsey&rsquo;s Building Blocks of Strategy may serve a similar function: an architecture that enables strategy leaders to ensure diverse contributions to strategy &mdash; human and artificial &mdash; can productively combine.</p>
<p>For strategy leaders navigating an era of extraordinary technological shocks, Baldwin's four decades of research point to a consistent conclusion: the answer to overwhelming complexity is not less complexity. It is better architecture.</p>
<h2>A Note on the Artwork</h2>
<p>Sir John Soane's Drawing Office, Sir John Soane's Museum, London. Photo: Gareth Gardner, 2023</p>
<p>The image accompanying this post is the <a href="https://drawingoffice.soane.org/about-drawing-office">Drawing Office</a> at <a href="https://www.soane.org/">Sir John Soane's Museum</a> in London &mdash; the oldest surviving architect's office in the world, recently restored and opened to the public for the first time in its two-hundred-year history.</p>
<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Soane">Soane</a> was one of the greatest English architects of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgian_era">Georgian era</a>, responsible for the <a href="https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/museum/online-collections/archive-gallery/soane-bank">Bank of England</a>, among other landmarks. He was also Professor of Architecture at the Royal Academy, and his home served simultaneously as a working office, a teaching space, and what contemporaries called "an Academy of Architecture." The Drawing Office sits at the heart of this: a small, ingeniously designed mezzanine platform, suspended on metal columns above the museum corridor below, lit by skylights that illuminated both the workspace and the collections beneath it. At its peak, six pupils worked here, shoulder to shoulder at long desks, twelve hours a day, six days a week.</p>
<p>What makes the Drawing Office remarkable for this post's purposes is what crowds its walls. Roughly 250 plaster casts of classical architectural elements &mdash; cornices, capitals, friezes, ornamental fragments &mdash; taken from ancient Greek and Roman buildings, hang on every available surface, even jostling on the ceiling joists. These were educational and generative, not decorative. Soane immersed his pupils in a vocabulary of architectural forms so they could study each element independently and recombine them in original compositions. During the recent restoration, conservators discovered that Soane had deliberately placed models of his own buildings alongside the ancient casts that inspired them, making the lineage between source and new creation visible.</p>
<p>The casts are in a sense, in Baldwin's terms, modules: self-contained components of a larger architectural language, each conforming to visible design rules of classical proportion and order, each helping to manage complexity that the apprentice gradually learns to master. The office itself is the architecture that makes the modules productive &mdash; a workspace designed so that the vocabulary is always present, always available for recombination, always in dialogue with the original designs being produced at the desks below.</p>
<p>This mirrors the argument of this post. Strategy leaders today face an abundance of frameworks, techniques, and AI-enabled capabilities. Without a shared architecture &mdash; a set of building blocks with defined interfaces &mdash; that abundance is overwhelming: fragments without a wall to hang on. With such an architecture, the fragments become a vocabulary. Each technique can be studied independently, applied selectively, and composed with others into original strategic work. The building blocks serve the same function as Soane's office: they create the environment in which diverse contributions combine into coherent design.</p>
<p>Last year, I had the pleasure of hosting a dinner for 25 chief strategy officers of <a href="https://www.mckinsey.com/capabilities/strategy-and-corporate-finance/our-insights/how-strategy-champions-win">Strategy Champion companies</a> at Sir John Soane's Museum. On our tour through the carefully designed and curated building, it was difficult not to think about what it means to build an environment for strategic thinking &mdash; one where the right tools, the right vocabulary, and the right people come together in a space deliberately designed for the work. Soane understood that great architecture does not emerge from a blank page. It emerges from deep familiarity with a rich vocabulary of forms, structured by an architecture that supports the craft. Baldwin's research suggests the same is true of great strategy.</p>
